    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "[Al](Cl)(Cl)Cl"
    ],
    "rationale": "The Fries rearrangement of phenyl acetate to 2-hydroxyacetophenone is a classic, simple, and unambiguous textbook example. It clearly demonstrates the core transformation: the migration of an acyl group from a phenolic oxygen to an ortho position on the aromatic ring, catalyzed by a Lewis acid (AlCl3). This example is minimal in structure, avoiding complex substituents that could cause ambiguity.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple phenyl acetate substrate, avoiding more complex aromatic systems that could overlap with other named reactions involving arenes. The transformation is a specific acyl migration, distinct from Claisen rearrangements (allyl migration), benzidine rearrangements (diarylamine rearrangement), or electrophilic aromatic substitution reactions like Friedel-Crafts acylation, as the acyl group originates from the substrate itself rather than an external acylating agent."
  }
}
